1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:01,730
Speaker 17: Hello, everyone, and welcome.

2
00:00:02,110 --> 00:00:03,749
I'm Premanand Ratnasabapathy.

3
00:00:04,439 --> 00:00:07,689
Over the past twenty-two years, I
have architected compliance systems

4
00:00:07,770 --> 00:00:09,630
processing millions of transactions daily.

5
00:00:10,120 --> 00:00:11,620
And here is what I actually learned.

6
00:00:12,220 --> 00:00:15,370
Modern financial institutions
possess massive data reserves, yet

7
00:00:15,429 --> 00:00:18,530
they lack real-time visibility into
their critical compliance workflows.

8
00:00:19,220 --> 00:00:22,940
Today, I'm going to show you how to
solve it, not with another database,

9
00:00:23,080 --> 00:00:26,170
not with another dashboard, but by
treating structured application logs

10
00:00:26,209 --> 00:00:29,840
as your primary intelligence layer,
and how that foundation becomes the

11
00:00:29,840 --> 00:00:33,519
precondition for AI-powered compliance
operation that actually work at scale.

12
00:00:34,019 --> 00:00:37,140
Let's start with a problem that we
all live with, even if we rarely talk

13
00:00:37,140 --> 00:00:39,140
about it This is the core problem.

14
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:40,330
Let me make it concrete.

15
00:00:40,950 --> 00:00:45,170
Modern financial institutions operate
across deeply fragmented architectures.

16
00:00:45,810 --> 00:00:48,489
You might have customer data
sitting in a legacy SQL database

17
00:00:48,540 --> 00:00:50,010
like Oracle or SQL Server.

18
00:00:50,540 --> 00:00:54,410
You have transaction details buried in a
NoSQL database like MongoDB or Cassandra.

19
00:00:54,910 --> 00:00:58,700
You have identity verification strapped
in a third-party system, which you

20
00:00:58,780 --> 00:01:00,190
even can't even directly query.

21
00:01:00,790 --> 00:01:04,290
On top of that, you have message queues
trying to handle workflow orchestration.

22
00:01:05,190 --> 00:01:08,290
Microservices spread across five
different deployment environments

23
00:01:08,520 --> 00:01:11,530
and APIs that are supposed to connect
everything when they're working.

24
00:01:12,270 --> 00:01:15,180
Now, imagine a system triggers
a transaction alert at ten AM.

25
00:01:15,840 --> 00:01:18,890
Your compliance analysts need to
know: Is this a false positive?

26
00:01:19,590 --> 00:01:21,390
What transactions preceded the alert?

27
00:01:21,830 --> 00:01:22,970
Did we respond in time?

28
00:01:23,490 --> 00:01:24,560
What's the audit trail?

29
00:01:25,140 --> 00:01:26,770
The answer should take thirty seconds.

30
00:01:27,090 --> 00:01:27,840
Where do you get it?

31
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:28,809
You don't.

32
00:01:29,330 --> 00:01:32,620
The story is scattered across five
systems with no single point of

33
00:01:32,650 --> 00:01:34,870
truth, and the consequences compound.

34
00:01:35,660 --> 00:01:39,130
Failed screenings go unnoticed
until manual review surfaces

35
00:01:39,130 --> 00:01:40,410
them, often too late.

36
00:01:41,180 --> 00:01:45,180
Compliance teams rely on lagging reports
instead of live operational state.

37
00:01:45,680 --> 00:01:48,510
By the time you assemble the data,
you have missed the regulatory window.

38
00:01:49,170 --> 00:01:53,820
Audit exposure increases exponentially,
and this is what operational blindness

39
00:01:53,820 --> 00:01:55,470
looks like, and it's a compliance risk

40
00:01:55,970 --> 00:01:57,310
So why hasn't this been solved?

41
00:01:57,670 --> 00:02:01,040
Because the traditional approach to
fixing it actually makes things worse.

42
00:02:01,940 --> 00:02:05,850
When you try to solve fragmentation
the old way, you run compliance queries

43
00:02:05,890 --> 00:02:08,430
across multiple databases simultaneously.

44
00:02:09,160 --> 00:02:11,190
You're doing heavy cross-database joins.

45
00:02:12,090 --> 00:02:15,570
Your compliance reports need to correlate
customer data from a relational database,

46
00:02:16,180 --> 00:02:19,890
transaction results from a non-relational
database, and hits from a third-party API.

47
00:02:20,350 --> 00:02:21,490
The joins are expensive.

48
00:02:22,420 --> 00:02:23,790
Resource contention shoots up.

49
00:02:24,310 --> 00:02:25,620
Latency cascades.

50
00:02:26,190 --> 00:02:28,670
Meanwhile, your production
transaction processing is slowing

51
00:02:28,670 --> 00:02:31,400
down because reporting is starving
the database connection pool.

52
00:02:32,340 --> 00:02:34,180
And then there is the
data correction problem.

53
00:02:34,569 --> 00:02:37,620
Dirty reads and phantom reads mean
your compliance state is wrong.

54
00:02:38,299 --> 00:02:40,199
You are making decisions
on corrupted data.

55
00:02:41,069 --> 00:02:42,600
The result is immediate and painful.

56
00:02:42,600 --> 00:02:45,560
SLA viol- SLA violations pile up.

57
00:02:46,540 --> 00:02:48,010
Fraud detection gets delayed.

58
00:02:48,669 --> 00:02:50,769
Manual troubleshooting
becomes the only option.

59
00:02:51,470 --> 00:02:53,329
Mean time to resolution skyrockets.

60
00:02:53,750 --> 00:02:55,260
Compliance deadlines get missed.

61
00:02:55,729 --> 00:02:56,860
I have seen this firsthand.

62
00:02:57,759 --> 00:02:59,540
Database-centric
observability doesn't scale.

63
00:03:00,389 --> 00:03:04,159
Every new service, every new vendor,
every new regulation makes it worse.

64
00:03:04,819 --> 00:03:07,020
You are fighting the
architecture, not the problem

65
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:09,820
Let's quantify what happens
when you do nothing.

66
00:03:10,580 --> 00:03:12,320
First, undetected failures.

67
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:14,800
A screening system fails silently.

68
00:03:15,700 --> 00:03:16,880
The transaction sits in a queue.

69
00:03:17,510 --> 00:03:19,140
Your system is supposed to alert you.

70
00:03:19,330 --> 00:03:19,940
It doesn't.

71
00:03:20,170 --> 00:03:20,550
Why?

72
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,920
Because the failure doesn't
appear in a single database query.

73
00:03:24,610 --> 00:03:28,290
It's a state spanning multiple services
that nobody's directly monitoring.

74
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:31,820
Then a customer calls about
a stuck payment, or worse, a

75
00:03:31,820 --> 00:03:33,200
regulator catches it first.

76
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:35,730
Second, stale intelligence.

77
00:03:36,290 --> 00:03:39,720
Your compliance team runs a report at the
end of day showing forty-seven failures.

78
00:03:40,250 --> 00:03:43,390
By the time the report is generated,
half of those are already resolved

79
00:03:43,520 --> 00:03:46,140
manually, and the compliance
team doesn't know about it.

80
00:03:46,650 --> 00:03:50,480
They investigate closed cases,
time wasted, risk unmitigated.

81
00:03:51,040 --> 00:03:52,210
Third, escalating cost.

82
00:03:52,930 --> 00:03:54,439
You add three new vendors.

83
00:03:54,960 --> 00:03:56,410
You migrate to microservices.

84
00:03:56,920 --> 00:03:59,489
Every new system makes the
coordination problem worse.

85
00:03:59,940 --> 00:04:03,930
Your ops team spends forty percent of
their time manually reconciling systems,

86
00:04:04,769 --> 00:04:06,240
and that's a regulatory exposure.

87
00:04:06,890 --> 00:04:10,320
Regulators ask, "Show me every
transaction processed for this

88
00:04:10,320 --> 00:04:14,430
customer in the last thirty days." Your
answer, "We will get back to you in a

89
00:04:14,430 --> 00:04:15,880
week." The hesitation is the problem.

90
00:04:16,380 --> 00:04:20,469
The price of an undetected compliance
failure is crippling regulatory penalties.

91
00:04:20,969 --> 00:04:24,450
The price of a delayed investigation
is compounding exposure.

92
00:04:25,100 --> 00:04:28,519
But the cost of fixing this architecture
is just a fraction of a single incident.

93
00:04:29,389 --> 00:04:32,560
Database-centric observability
is structurally unsustainable.

94
00:04:33,029 --> 00:04:34,280
You need a different approach

95
00:04:34,780 --> 00:04:35,850
Here is a core insight.

96
00:04:36,220 --> 00:04:38,310
Stop treating logs as
an operational waste.

97
00:04:38,580 --> 00:04:40,360
Make them your primary intelligence layer.

98
00:04:40,970 --> 00:04:44,800
Instead of polling database for compliance
state, applications emit structured

99
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:48,890
logs that become the source of truth for
what's happening operationally, real-time,

100
00:04:49,069 --> 00:04:51,710
immutable, distributed, ready for AI.

101
00:04:52,479 --> 00:04:54,750
The architecture has four
layers working together.

102
00:04:54,950 --> 00:04:56,759
First, the wrapper library.

103
00:04:57,309 --> 00:04:59,500
Developers import a single JAR dependency.

104
00:04:59,770 --> 00:05:03,269
The library automatically instruments
their code to emit structured logs.

105
00:05:03,949 --> 00:05:05,659
Zero changes to business logic.

106
00:05:06,309 --> 00:05:10,339
Every request, response, error,
and business event gets logged in a

107
00:05:10,340 --> 00:05:12,200
standardized format automatically.

108
00:05:13,159 --> 00:05:14,629
Second, log schema.

109
00:05:15,419 --> 00:05:16,719
Consistency is everything.

110
00:05:17,189 --> 00:05:20,629
Every log follows the same
structure, predictable fields.

111
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:25,409
This is what makes logs consumable
by machines, databases, search

112
00:05:25,409 --> 00:05:27,269
engines, and eventually LLMs.

113
00:05:28,219 --> 00:05:29,739
Third, correlation ID.

114
00:05:30,029 --> 00:05:31,000
This is the breakthrough.

115
00:05:31,869 --> 00:05:36,029
Each business entity, customer
account, screening case, transaction,

116
00:05:36,469 --> 00:05:39,869
gets tagged with a correlation ID
as it flows through your system.

117
00:05:40,369 --> 00:05:43,419
One customer's entire compliance
journey can be restructured

118
00:05:43,419 --> 00:05:44,789
without a single database join.

119
00:05:45,499 --> 00:05:47,729
Fourth, ingestion pipeline.

120
00:05:48,189 --> 00:05:49,159
Real-time ingestion.

121
00:05:49,979 --> 00:05:53,109
Logs flow through applications to
a centralized intelligence layer,

122
00:05:53,559 --> 00:05:55,209
decoupled from the transaction path.

123
00:05:55,849 --> 00:05:58,419
Failures in the pipeline don't
break customer transactions.

124
00:05:58,919 --> 00:06:00,709
What this enables is straightforward.

125
00:06:01,129 --> 00:06:03,569
You add observability without
touching production code.

126
00:06:04,289 --> 00:06:07,069
You span distributed systems
without database joins.

127
00:06:07,619 --> 00:06:09,619
You create real-time
compliance narratives.

128
00:06:10,019 --> 00:06:12,469
You build AI-consumable
operational memory.

129
00:06:13,109 --> 00:06:16,639
The key advantage here is that each
layer is independently deployable,

130
00:06:17,139 --> 00:06:20,379
requiring no changes to production
database schemas or core business logic.

131
00:06:21,049 --> 00:06:22,609
You don't need a big bang migration.

132
00:06:23,149 --> 00:06:27,309
You instrument one service, see
the benefits, instrument the next.

133
00:06:27,879 --> 00:06:30,089
Each step is a low risk and high value

134
00:06:30,589 --> 00:06:31,989
This is where the magic happens.

135
00:06:32,549 --> 00:06:36,189
How do you get structured logs everywhere
without rewriting your entire code base?

136
00:06:36,939 --> 00:06:39,689
The wrapper library approach
is deceptively simple.

137
00:06:40,389 --> 00:06:43,059
Imagine a developer in your team
writing a screening service.

138
00:06:43,669 --> 00:06:47,129
Instead of manually sprinkling log
statements everywhere, developer

139
00:06:47,139 --> 00:06:48,549
imports the compliance logger.

140
00:06:49,089 --> 00:06:49,579
One import.

141
00:06:50,559 --> 00:06:55,069
The library wraps the method, intercepts
the inputs and outputs, and emits

142
00:06:55,069 --> 00:06:56,649
a structured log automatically.

143
00:06:57,299 --> 00:07:00,699
The developer doesn't write a single
log statement, the library handles it.

144
00:07:01,199 --> 00:07:04,919
What gets captured automatically is
comprehensive request and response

145
00:07:04,919 --> 00:07:09,139
metadata with precise timestamps,
which service ran this code and which

146
00:07:09,139 --> 00:07:14,179
environment, exception type, messages,
and stack trace, and critically, business

147
00:07:14,179 --> 00:07:18,149
identifiers like customer account number,
transaction ID, case reference, rule ID.

148
00:07:18,879 --> 00:07:21,799
The non-intrusive design is
where adoption becomes fast.

149
00:07:22,339 --> 00:07:24,789
Your engineers don't need to
learn a new logging framework.

150
00:07:25,549 --> 00:07:26,939
They don't need to remember to log.

151
00:07:27,279 --> 00:07:29,999
They don't need to coordinate with
the compliance team about what to log.

152
00:07:30,429 --> 00:07:31,609
The library handles it.

153
00:07:32,259 --> 00:07:33,129
Why this matters.

154
00:07:33,809 --> 00:07:36,309
Transactional logging puts
the burdens on developers.

155
00:07:36,759 --> 00:07:41,229
Either they don't log enough, you're
missing context, or they log too much,

156
00:07:41,589 --> 00:07:43,409
creating noise and performance impact.

157
00:07:44,069 --> 00:07:46,409
This library finds a
sweet spot automatically.

158
00:07:46,869 --> 00:07:51,309
It captures what compliance needs without
burdening the application Here is where

159
00:07:51,309 --> 00:07:53,349
the architecture gets com-- sophisticated.

160
00:07:53,879 --> 00:07:57,579
You can't have complaints logging
slow down your transaction, so we

161
00:07:57,579 --> 00:07:59,029
use three layers of decoupling.

162
00:07:59,529 --> 00:08:01,819
First, an async ring buffer.

163
00:08:02,589 --> 00:08:05,979
When a transaction processes, the
request comes in, the complaints

164
00:08:06,009 --> 00:08:10,039
logger emits an event into the
log-free ring buffer in memory, and

165
00:08:10,039 --> 00:08:11,739
the transaction continues immediately.

166
00:08:12,429 --> 00:08:15,499
The log event is captured, but
the transaction part doesn't wait.

167
00:08:15,819 --> 00:08:16,809
This is non-blocking.

168
00:08:17,499 --> 00:08:19,679
The ring buffer is a
fixed-size circular queue.

169
00:08:20,489 --> 00:08:22,459
Microseconds per operation.

170
00:08:22,959 --> 00:08:24,579
Why a ring buffer and not a queue?

171
00:08:24,839 --> 00:08:27,389
Because queues allocate
memory as they grow.

172
00:08:28,089 --> 00:08:30,579
Under high load, that
allocation becomes expensive.

173
00:08:31,309 --> 00:08:35,019
Ring buffers use pre-allocated
memory, consistent performance,

174
00:08:35,359 --> 00:08:36,439
predictable latency.

175
00:08:36,939 --> 00:08:38,929
Second, background worker pool.

176
00:08:39,499 --> 00:08:42,929
Separator threads, not the
transaction threads, drain the ring

177
00:08:42,939 --> 00:08:46,559
buffer and forward events into an
ingestion pipeline asynchronously.

178
00:08:47,249 --> 00:08:50,259
If the ring buffer fills
faster than workers can drain

179
00:08:50,259 --> 00:08:52,499
it, old events get discarded.

180
00:08:53,419 --> 00:08:56,099
Not transaction data,
just complaints telemetry.

181
00:08:56,679 --> 00:08:58,419
The transaction is always protected.

182
00:08:59,339 --> 00:09:01,149
Third, decoupled injection.

183
00:09:01,899 --> 00:09:04,239
The injection pipeline runs independently.

184
00:09:04,629 --> 00:09:08,319
If the ingestion system is down,
if the network is slow, if the

185
00:09:08,319 --> 00:09:11,689
database is laggy, none of it
affects your transaction processing.

186
00:09:12,149 --> 00:09:13,999
This is critical for financial systems.

187
00:09:14,739 --> 00:09:17,669
Complaints infrastructure can
never become an availability risk.

188
00:09:18,489 --> 00:09:21,699
Real performance numbers, ring
buffer insertion is two hundred

189
00:09:21,699 --> 00:09:22,979
to five hundred nanoseconds.

190
00:09:23,579 --> 00:09:27,149
Worker thread drain is asynchronous
with zero impact on transaction path.

191
00:09:27,959 --> 00:09:30,329
Ingestion failure doesn't
propagate back to the application.

192
00:09:30,999 --> 00:09:33,479
Overhead per application is
less than one microsecond.

193
00:09:34,099 --> 00:09:35,809
This is invisible to your customers.

194
00:09:36,619 --> 00:09:37,759
The guarantee is absolute.

195
00:09:37,759 --> 00:09:41,399
Observability infrastructure must
never become a performance liability.

196
00:09:42,069 --> 00:09:45,969
The architecture is engineered for full
decoupling from the transaction path.

197
00:09:46,629 --> 00:09:49,589
You get complete visibility
without paying any performance cost

198
00:09:50,089 --> 00:09:53,589
This is where structured logs stop
being just monitoring data and

199
00:09:53,589 --> 00:09:55,209
become operational intelligence.

200
00:09:55,709 --> 00:09:58,889
Instead of using infrastructure
identifiers like request ID or

201
00:09:58,929 --> 00:10:00,759
trace ID, use business identifiers.

202
00:10:01,209 --> 00:10:04,579
When the system triggers an alert,
they get tagged with correlation

203
00:10:04,579 --> 00:10:06,649
IDs, customer account, transaction
ID, case ID, and this customer data

204
00:10:06,659 --> 00:10:10,809
flow through your entire system like
screening service, enrichment service,

205
00:10:11,259 --> 00:10:12,889
response service, alerting service.

206
00:10:13,319 --> 00:10:16,399
Every single log event gets tagged
with the same correlation ID.

207
00:10:17,329 --> 00:10:18,519
Here is how the process works.

208
00:10:19,389 --> 00:10:21,109
Step one: Event emitted.

209
00:10:21,659 --> 00:10:24,829
A transaction arrives at
the service at ten AM.

210
00:10:25,539 --> 00:10:28,889
A structured log is created
with timestamp, service name,

211
00:10:29,189 --> 00:10:33,009
correlation ID, event type,
transaction ID, and the result.

212
00:10:33,879 --> 00:10:38,439
The same transaction flows to the data
enrichment service and gets a new log with

213
00:10:38,439 --> 00:10:42,749
the same correlation ID, then to alert
service with the same correlation ID.

214
00:10:43,389 --> 00:10:47,509
Same customer, same transaction,
three different systems correlated.

215
00:10:48,419 --> 00:10:50,269
Step two: Events correlated.

216
00:10:51,249 --> 00:10:53,529
The ingestion layer
receives all these events.

217
00:10:53,999 --> 00:10:57,239
It groups them by correlation
ID and sorts them by timestamp.

218
00:10:57,749 --> 00:11:01,239
No database query, no cross-service
join, just grouping and

219
00:11:01,239 --> 00:11:02,509
sorting in the ingestion layer.

220
00:11:03,439 --> 00:11:05,609
Step three: Journey reconstructed.

221
00:11:06,109 --> 00:11:08,979
An analyst search for the complete
journey for a specific account.

222
00:11:08,979 --> 00:11:12,159
The system returns a
chronological narrative.

223
00:11:12,659 --> 00:11:16,499
Transaction initiated at ten AM
with the potential hit detected.

224
00:11:17,189 --> 00:11:21,419
Enrichment completed at ten AM
one second with a risk score

225
00:11:21,429 --> 00:11:22,309
of zero point eight seven.

226
00:11:23,299 --> 00:11:27,369
Alert generated at ten AM two
second with a critical severity.

227
00:11:28,289 --> 00:11:29,659
Case created and assigned.

228
00:11:30,369 --> 00:11:31,949
Analyst reviewed enrichment data.

229
00:11:32,469 --> 00:11:35,269
Investigation completed and
false positive confirmed.

230
00:11:35,589 --> 00:11:37,193
Alert closed with no regulatory action.

231
00:11:37,193 --> 00:11:39,329
A complete immutable timestamp sequence.

232
00:11:39,449 --> 00:11:44,369
The key advantage, no database join, no
cross-service queries, no coordination

233
00:11:44,369 --> 00:11:46,429
between teams and different data sources.

234
00:11:46,999 --> 00:11:49,779
Pure event correlation based
on business identifiers.

235
00:11:50,559 --> 00:11:53,379
This scales to thousands of
events per customer per day.

236
00:11:53,819 --> 00:11:56,059
Milliseconds to reconstruct
the full timeline.

237
00:11:56,969 --> 00:11:58,359
Why this matters for compliance?

238
00:11:58,749 --> 00:12:02,189
Regulators ask, "Walk me through
the exactly what happened with this

239
00:12:02,189 --> 00:12:06,039
customer." You show them the complete
timestamp immutable sequence of events.

240
00:12:06,269 --> 00:12:08,069
No gaps, no contradiction.

241
00:12:08,189 --> 00:12:09,669
That's the evidence trial they need

242
00:12:10,169 --> 00:12:13,009
Now all these correlated logs
become operational intelligence

243
00:12:13,069 --> 00:12:14,639
visible through a single dashboard.

244
00:12:15,049 --> 00:12:16,459
One place to see everything.

245
00:12:17,099 --> 00:12:20,279
That dashboard shows you
live workflow visibility.

246
00:12:20,839 --> 00:12:22,599
How many customers are
currently in screening?

247
00:12:23,149 --> 00:12:25,219
How many have been flagged
