Red for critical, screening is failing.

305
00:15:14,869 --> 00:15:16,739
Yellow for warning, performance degraded.

306
00:15:17,049 --> 00:15:18,749
Blue for info, maintenance window.

307
00:15:19,249 --> 00:15:21,649
Multiple channel notifications
happens instantly.

308
00:15:22,239 --> 00:15:25,809
Email to the compliance team, Slack
message to the incidents channel,

309
00:15:25,809 --> 00:15:29,929
PagerDuty alert to a on-call engineer,
auto-generated incident ticket in

310
00:15:29,929 --> 00:15:33,779
your ticketing system, SMS to the
on-call manager if critical enough.

311
00:15:34,689 --> 00:15:37,179
Why automated alerts
matter is straightforward.

312
00:15:37,919 --> 00:15:42,179
Traditionally, an alert fires, an email
goes out, someone reads it or doesn't.

313
00:15:42,609 --> 00:15:44,089
They think about whether to act.

314
00:15:44,719 --> 00:15:46,249
They pull up dashboards manually.

315
00:15:46,269 --> 00:15:48,349
Fifteen minutes later, they
understand the problem.

316
00:15:48,749 --> 00:15:51,939
With automation, the alert
fires, the incident is created,

317
00:15:52,259 --> 00:15:53,959
the on-call engineer is paged.

318
00:15:54,399 --> 00:15:56,929
By the time they check their
phone, they already have context.

319
00:15:57,019 --> 00:15:58,619
They don't have to start from zero.

320
00:15:59,179 --> 00:16:00,479
They start with intelligence.

321
00:16:00,979 --> 00:16:03,039
Escalation workflows
handle the complexity.

322
00:16:03,469 --> 00:16:05,889
Not alerts need the same response.

323
00:16:06,389 --> 00:16:09,609
A critical screening failure escalates
the on-call engineer immediately.

324
00:16:09,799 --> 00:16:13,069
If not acknowledged in two minutes,
the compliance manager is alerted.

325
00:16:13,509 --> 00:16:17,054
If still not acknowledged at five
minutes, the VP of compliance is alerted.

326
00:16:17,054 --> 00:16:21,529
A latency increase might ha-- just
go to Slack without paging everyone.

327
00:16:22,449 --> 00:16:23,729
The impact is dramatic.

328
00:16:24,379 --> 00:16:27,399
Before log-centric intelligence,
a sanction screening fails.

329
00:16:27,669 --> 00:16:29,659
It's silently at three o'clock.

330
00:16:30,229 --> 00:16:33,599
By four o'clock, a customer calls
complaining, and by four thirty, an

331
00:16:33,599 --> 00:16:36,759
engineer is scraping logs, and by
five o'clock root cause is identified.

332
00:16:37,279 --> 00:16:38,929
By five fifteen, the fix is deployed.

333
00:16:39,459 --> 00:16:42,949
Fifty-four minutes With log-centric
intelligence, screening failure

334
00:16:42,989 --> 00:16:44,339
is directed automatically.

335
00:16:44,819 --> 00:16:49,059
The PagerDuty alerts the on-call
engineer, and by three, four o'clock,

336
00:16:49,109 --> 00:16:53,019
the engineer pulls up the dashboard,
sees the failure spikes, sees the

337
00:16:53,019 --> 00:16:55,139
root cause in correlated logs.

338
00:16:55,489 --> 00:16:57,049
The fix is identified and deployed.

339
00:16:57,519 --> 00:17:00,229
By four, the service has recovered
with zero customer impact.

340
00:17:00,749 --> 00:17:04,109
Three-minute incident versus
fifty-four-minute incident.

341
00:17:04,609 --> 00:17:06,439
That's the power of
proactive intelligence.

342
00:17:06,939 --> 00:17:07,929
Here is the critical insight.

343
00:17:08,369 --> 00:17:12,099
Structured logs are the precondition
for trustworthy AI in compliance.

344
00:17:12,869 --> 00:17:17,669
LLMs work by finding patterns in massive
amounts of text, but they hallucinate

345
00:17:17,739 --> 00:17:21,429
when the data is inconsistent,
incomplete, or contradictory.

346
00:17:22,159 --> 00:17:25,799
Imagine asking an LLM, "Why does
this sanction screening fail?"

347
00:17:26,669 --> 00:17:30,189
Without structured logs, you feed
the LLM a pile of unstructured

348
00:17:30,199 --> 00:17:34,509
text from multiple systems, some
formatted differently, some missing

349
00:17:34,509 --> 00:17:36,769
dates, some contradicting each other.

350
00:17:37,439 --> 00:17:40,329
The LLM tries to reason about
it and makes up an answer.

351
00:17:40,899 --> 00:17:43,109
The customer's name contained
a special character that

352
00:17:43,109 --> 00:17:44,379
the system couldn't process.

353
00:17:44,799 --> 00:17:48,039
That sounds plausible, but it's
wrong, and you made a compliance

354
00:17:48,039 --> 00:17:50,109
decision based on LLM hallucination.

355
00:17:50,879 --> 00:17:55,139
With structured logs, you feed the LLM
the exact same incident, but structured.

356
00:17:55,709 --> 00:17:57,829
The LLM reads it and reads correctly.

357
00:17:58,519 --> 00:18:02,009
The enrichment service was down at
the time, so screening failed because

358
00:18:02,039 --> 00:18:03,619
it couldn't enrich the customer data.

359
00:18:03,769 --> 00:18:04,429
That's the truth.

360
00:18:04,689 --> 00:18:05,609
That's trustworthy.

361
00:18:06,399 --> 00:18:09,129
The three preconditions for
trustworthy AI are clear.

362
00:18:09,399 --> 00:18:11,649
First, predictable field structures.

363
00:18:12,109 --> 00:18:14,529
Every log has the same
fields in the same positions.

364
00:18:14,929 --> 00:18:15,669
Consistency.

365
00:18:16,259 --> 00:18:18,009
The LLM learns what to expect.

366
00:18:18,959 --> 00:18:20,879
Second, business contextual metadata.

367
00:18:20,879 --> 00:18:23,459
The logs aren't full of
infrastructure noise.

368
00:18:23,869 --> 00:18:25,379
They are full of business events.

369
00:18:25,899 --> 00:18:29,259
The LLM reasons about
compliance, not service.

370
00:18:29,899 --> 00:18:32,429
Third, chronological
order operational memory.

371
00:18:32,929 --> 00:18:34,629
Events are timestamped and ordered.

372
00:18:35,069 --> 00:18:37,979
The LLM can see
cause-and-effect relationships.

373
00:18:38,769 --> 00:18:40,779
Unstructured logs are a wall of text.

374
00:18:41,289 --> 00:18:44,059
An LLM tries to parse
this, and it's ambiguous.

375
00:18:44,629 --> 00:18:47,199
Structured logs eliminate
that ambiguity entirely.

376
00:18:47,499 --> 00:18:50,209
Clear, machine-readable, LLM-consumable.

377
00:18:50,709 --> 00:18:53,429
In regulated industries,
you can't rely on guesses.

378
00:18:53,939 --> 00:18:56,809
When an LLM makes a recommendation
about compliance actions, you

379
00:18:56,809 --> 00:18:58,189
need to understand exactly why.

380
00:18:58,669 --> 00:19:00,679
Structured logs give
you that transparency.

381
00:19:01,159 --> 00:19:05,559
The LLM reasons about the data,
and you can't audit every step

382
00:19:06,059 --> 00:19:07,369
These are theoretical.

383
00:19:07,529 --> 00:19:08,729
They are real case uses.

384
00:19:09,199 --> 00:19:12,259
Use case one: natural
language investigations.

385
00:19:12,659 --> 00:19:17,049
Today's reality, complaints analyst
says, "I need all screening failures

386
00:19:17,119 --> 00:19:20,729
for high-risk customers in the last
twenty-four hours." An engineer's

387
00:19:20,729 --> 00:19:24,269
response is, "I'll write you a SQL query,
give you in thirty minutes." Thirty

388
00:19:24,269 --> 00:19:25,899
minutes later, you have a spreadsheet.

389
00:19:26,469 --> 00:19:27,709
But are the results complete?

390
00:19:28,219 --> 00:19:31,999
With the structured logs and LLM, the
analyst types in a complaints dashboard,

391
00:19:32,419 --> 00:19:35,599
"Show all failures for high-risk
accounts in the last twenty-four

392
00:19:35,599 --> 00:19:40,629
hours." The LLM interprets this: AM
failures causing screening service

393
00:19:40,629 --> 00:19:42,759
events with results equals error.

394
00:19:43,589 --> 00:19:47,349
High-risk accounts means accounts with
risk score greater than zero point seven.

395
00:19:47,899 --> 00:19:52,069
Last twenty-four hours means timestamp
greater than now minus eight thousand

396
00:19:52,069 --> 00:19:53,599
six hundred and four hundred seconds.

397
00:19:54,499 --> 00:19:58,529
It queries the structured log database
instantly, returns twenty-three failures.

398
00:19:59,079 --> 00:20:02,239
Analyst sees them all in context
with full transaction history.

399
00:20:02,909 --> 00:20:05,969
Complaints analysts aren't SQL
experts, they are domain experts.

400
00:20:06,419 --> 00:20:09,509
They should ask questions in
English and get answers immediately.

401
00:20:10,439 --> 00:20:13,529
Use case two: automated
incident summaries.

402
00:20:14,189 --> 00:20:15,269
An incident happens.

403
00:20:15,789 --> 00:20:17,989
Screening service is
down for fifteen minutes.

404
00:20:18,309 --> 00:20:21,189
Traditionally, an engineer spends
two hours manually analyzing when it

405
00:20:21,189 --> 00:20:25,689
started, how many transactions were
affected, what's the root cause was,

406
00:20:26,049 --> 00:20:28,329
what was the fix, then writes a summary.

407
00:20:28,789 --> 00:20:31,649
Only after this manual investigation
came the complaints team understand

408
00:20:31,649 --> 00:20:35,429
what happened With structured logs
and LLM, within 60 seconds, an

409
00:20:35,429 --> 00:20:36,739
automated summary is generated.

410
00:20:37,229 --> 00:20:40,879
Incident summary: Sanction screening down
for twelve minutes thirty-four seconds.

411
00:20:41,379 --> 00:20:42,929
Database connection pool exhausted.

412
00:20:43,199 --> 00:20:46,039
Cause: Bulk screening job
consuming all connection.

413
00:20:46,589 --> 00:20:50,519
Impact: Five hundred and forty-seven
transactions queued, zero lost.

414
00:20:50,839 --> 00:20:52,499
All auto retried successfully.

415
00:20:52,899 --> 00:20:55,649
Resolution: Bulk job rate limited.

416
00:20:56,029 --> 00:20:56,979
Service recovered.

417
00:20:57,509 --> 00:20:58,869
Customers affected: none.

418
00:20:59,389 --> 00:21:03,309
Recommendation: Implement circuit breaker
to prevent bulk jobs from consuming more

419
00:21:03,309 --> 00:21:04,769
than fifty percent of connection pool.

420
00:21:05,359 --> 00:21:06,839
This is generated automatically.

421
00:21:07,359 --> 00:21:09,579
Compliance team gets
full context immediately.

422
00:21:10,059 --> 00:21:12,669
Investigation time drops from
two hours to thirty seconds.

423
00:21:13,129 --> 00:21:15,889
Use case three: Intelligent
root cause analysis.

424
00:21:15,889 --> 00:21:17,759
AML workflow is slow.

425
00:21:17,939 --> 00:21:18,829
Screening time is out.

426
00:21:19,709 --> 00:21:22,939
Analyst manually checks database
performance, network latency,

427
00:21:23,029 --> 00:21:24,879
service logs, message queue depth.

428
00:21:25,409 --> 00:21:29,679
Three separate investigations, each
with incomplete information, takes days.

429
00:21:30,079 --> 00:21:34,319
With structured logs and LLM, the analyst
asks, "Why are the screenings taking

430
00:21:34,319 --> 00:21:39,009
fifteen-plus seconds today?" The LLM
has access to screening service latency,

431
00:21:39,599 --> 00:21:44,329
enrichment service latency, database
query time, message queue depth, network

432
00:21:44,339 --> 00:21:47,179
conditions, external API latency.

433
00:21:47,179 --> 00:21:49,519
It analyzes all of this
and sees the pattern.

434
00:21:50,029 --> 00:21:53,589
Screening requests average five
hundred milliseconds, but enrichment

435
00:21:53,669 --> 00:21:55,429
requests average eight seconds.

436
00:21:56,079 --> 00:21:58,479
Enrichment only started
slowing thirty minutes ago.

437
00:21:58,869 --> 00:22:01,459
That coincides with a new
customer batch process starting.

438
00:22:02,209 --> 00:22:06,349
The batch job is consuming ninety-five
percent of enrichment service resources.

439
00:22:07,149 --> 00:22:08,579
The LLM generates a summary.

440
00:22:09,109 --> 00:22:12,189
AML screening latency increased
at fourteen thirty UC.

441
00:22:12,989 --> 00:22:16,299
Root cause: New customer batch
enrichment job consuming ninety-five

442
00:22:16,299 --> 00:22:18,249
percent of enrichment source resources.

443
00:22:18,929 --> 00:22:23,289
Recommendation: Pause batch job
or implement priority queuing.

444
00:22:24,119 --> 00:22:26,419
Expected resolution: Fifteen minutes.

445
00:22:26,789 --> 00:22:29,749
All of this correlation
analysis happens immediately.

446
00:22:30,709 --> 00:22:34,439
The LLM surfaces insights that would
take your team days to uncover.

447
00:22:35,019 --> 00:22:38,599
You are not replacing compliance analysts,
you are multiplying their effectiveness.

448
00:22:38,989 --> 00:22:40,829
They ask questions in natural language.

449
00:22:41,139 --> 00:22:44,009
They get intelligent answers
backed by structured data.

450
00:22:44,499 --> 00:22:46,329
They make faster, better decisions.

451
00:22:46,849 --> 00:22:49,539
Investigation time goes from
two hours to five minutes.

452
00:22:49,999 --> 00:22:52,699
False positive resolution from
thirty minutes to five minutes.

453
00:22:53,229 --> 00:22:55,909
Incident response from forty-five
minutes to ten minutes.

454
00:22:56,669 --> 00:22:59,389
Regulatory investigation prep
from eight hours to one hour.

455
00:23:00,269 --> 00:23:00,999
These savings compound.

456
00:23:01,499 --> 00:23:05,259
Production-grade architecture means
addressing scalability, security,

457
00:23:05,499 --> 00:23:07,529
and AI safeguards simultaneously.

458
00:23:08,029 --> 00:23:08,189
Scalability.

459
00:23:08,729 --> 00:23:11,599
As compliance volumes grows,
you need to scale horizontally.

460
00:23:12,019 --> 00:23:15,189
The ingestion pipelines handle
this through distributed ingestion.

461
00:23:15,879 --> 00:23:19,299
Log events are partitioned and
routed to multiple ingestion nodes.

462
00:23:19,659 --> 00:23:22,509
If one node is down,
other handles the traffic.

463
00:23:22,839 --> 00:23:24,139
No single point of failure.

464
00:23:24,629 --> 00:23:25,829
Horizontal replication.

465
00:23:26,549 --> 00:23:30,109
Critical compliance data is replicated
across multiple availability zones.

466
00:23:30,469 --> 00:23:33,709
If a data center goes down, your
compliance data is safe elsewhere.

467
00:23:34,159 --> 00:23:35,119
Partition indexing.

468
00:23:35,569 --> 00:23:38,569
Logs are indexed by date,
by account, by service.

469
00:23:39,249 --> 00:23:42,199
You don't search all ten billion
logs to answer what happened

470
00:23:42,199 --> 00:23:43,209
with this customer today.

471
00:23:43,529 --> 00:23:46,469
You search the partition for
today's log for this customer.

472
00:23:47,189 --> 00:23:48,859
Orders of magnitude faster.

473
00:23:49,189 --> 00:23:50,019
Real numbers.

474
00:23:50,359 --> 00:23:53,099
We have scaled this to one million
compliance events per second.

475
00:23:53,269 --> 00:23:56,019
That's eighty-six billion events
per day, still responsive.

476
00:23:56,869 --> 00:23:58,349
Security, this is critical.

477
00:23:59,019 --> 00:24:03,939
Your logs contain sensitive data, customer
names, account numbers, transactions.

478
00:24:04,279 --> 00:24:05,699
You can't expose that to LLMs.

479
00:24:05,819 --> 00:24:08,139
You can't expose it to
anybody without authorization.

480
00:24:08,619 --> 00:24:12,019
Field-level masking happens before
logs can reach the observability layer.

481
00:24:12,539 --> 00:24:15,869
Raw log with a customer name
account number, transaction amount.

482
00:24:16,709 --> 00:24:19,919
Masked logs, those fields are
replaced with masked placeholders.

483
00:24:20,669 --> 00:24:23,439
The business logic is
preserved, the PII is protected.

484
00:24:24,269 --> 00:24:27,099
Role-based access control ensures
not everyone sees everything.

485
00:24:27,459 --> 00:24:30,809
Compliance analysts see masked logs
for accounts they are assigned.

486
00:24:31,409 --> 00:24:34,839
Investigators can request
unmasked access with audit trail.

487
00:24:35,579 --> 00:24:37,549
Engineers see only service-level logs.

488
00:24:38,089 --> 00:24:39,959
Auditors see aggregated metrics.

